Loan default prediction¶

Context¶

A major proportion of retail bank profit comes from interests in the form of home loans. These loans are borrowed by regular income/high-earning customers. Banks are most fearful of defaulters, as bad loans (NPA) usually eat up a major chunk of their profits. Therefore, it is important for banks to be judicious while approving loans for their customer base. The approval process for the loans is multifaceted. Through this process, the bank tries to check the creditworthiness of the applicant on the basis of a manual study of various aspects of the application. The entire process is not only effort-intensive but also prone to wrong judgment/approval owing to human error and biases. There have been attempts by many banks to automate this process by using heuristics. But with the advent of data science and machine learning, the focus has shifted to building machines that can learn this approval process and make it free of biases and more efficient. At the same time, one important thing to keep in mind is to make sure that the machine does not learn the biases that previously crept in because of the human approval process.

Problem Statement¶

A bank's consumer credit department aims to simplify the decision-making process for home equity lines of credit to be accepted. To do this, they will adopt the Equal Credit Opportunity Act's guidelines to establish an empirically derived and statistically sound model for credit scoring. The model will be based on the data obtained via the existing loan underwriting process from recent applicants who have been given credit. The model will be built from predictive modeling techniques, but the model created must be interpretable enough to provide a justification for any adverse behavior (rejections).

Objective¶

Build a classification model to predict clients who are likely to default on their loan and give recommendations to the bank on the important features to consider while approving a loan.

Data Dictionary¶

The Home Equity dataset (HMEQ) contains baseline and loan performance information for recent home equity loans. The target (BAD) is a binary variable that indicates whether an applicant has ultimately defaulted or has been severely delinquent. There are 12 input variables registered for each applicant.

  • BAD: 1 = Client defaulted on loan, 0 = loan repaid
  • LOAN: Amount of loan approved
  • MORTDUE: Amount due on the existing mortgage
  • VALUE: Current value of the property
  • REASON: Reason for the loan request (HomeImp = home improvement, DebtCon= debt consolidation which means taking out a new loan to pay off other liabilities and consumer debts)
  • JOB: The type of job that loan applicant has such as manager, self, etc.
  • YOJ: Years at present job
  • DEROG: Number of major derogatory reports (which indicates serious delinquency or late payments).
  • DELINQ: Number of delinquent credit lines (a line of credit becomes delinquent when a borrower does not make the minimum required payments 30 to 60 days past the day on which the payments were due)
  • CLAGE: Age of the oldest credit line in months
  • NINQ: Number of recent credit inquiries
  • CLNO: Number of existing credit lines
  • DEBTINC: Debt-to-income ratio (all monthly debt payments divided by gross monthly income. This number is one of the ways lenders measure a borrowers ability to manage the monthly payments to repay the money they plan to borrow)

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Leading Questions:

  1. What is the range of values for the loan amount variable "LOAN"?
  2. How does the distribution of years at present job "YOJ" vary across the dataset?
  3. How many unique categories are there in the REASON variable?
  4. What is the most common category in the JOB variable?
  5. Is there a relationship between the REASON variable and the proportion of applicants who defaulted on their loan?
  6. Do applicants who default have a significantly different loan amount compared to those who repay their loan?
  7. Is there a correlation between the value of the property and the loan default rate?
  8. Do applicants who default have a significantly different mortgage amount compared to those who repay their loan?
In [11]:
#Creating a function to plot both boxplot and histogram of numerical varibles
def box_histplot(field, color, title, xlabel, mean = True, showkde = True, bins='auto'):
    '''
    Function to plot a boxplot and a histplot from numerical varible 
    with vertical ratio of 0.25, 0.75, respectively. 
    
    field: Numerical column to plot 
    color: hex color code for both plots
    title: title for specific plot
    xlabel: specific label for the x axis
    '''
    fig,ax = plt.subplots(2,1, figsize=(8,5), gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': [0.25, 0.75]}, sharex=True)

    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=field, showmeans= mean, color= color,ax=ax[0])
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=field, bins=bins, kde = showkde, color = color,ax=ax[1])

    # Add mean to the histogram
    ax[1].axvline(data[field].mean(), color = "green", linestyle = "--") 
    # Add median to the histogram
    ax[1].axvline(data[field].median(), color = "black", linestyle = "-") 

    fig.suptitle(title)
    ax[0].set(xlabel='')
    ax[1].set(xlabel= xlabel)
    plt.show()

Now we can plot how the mean debt-to-income ratio varies depending on the job in order to see if there is any visible pattern.

In [16]:
# Setting figure
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))
# Plotting debt-to-income ratio vs job and defaulted
sns.pointplot(data=data, x="ratio_debtinc", y="job", hue="defaulted", order=jobord, palette='pastel')
plt.title('Debt-to-income ratio by job and default status', fontsize=15)
plt.xlabel('Debt to income ratio')
plt.ylabel('Profession')
plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • The majority of clients are not defaulters, as it was previously stated around 20% of clientes turned out to be defaulters.
  • Regarding job distribution, most clients job is labeled as Others while the profession with least clients is Sales.
  • With respect of people years in their current job, it shows a right-skewed distribution with a mean of nearly 9 years. Very few people in the dataset has more than 28 years in their current job.
  • In terms of debt-to-income ratio, the average person has a debt of 33 times their income. In this case, few people has a debt of half their income, meaning they perceive an income of twice their debt. On the other hand, few people has a debt of 53 times their income, and only one person has a debt of 203 times its income.
  • Respecting the last plot, we notice that in every job category the clients that paid their loans has in average a smaller debt-to-income ratio. On the other hand, despite Sales and Self, being the categories with least clients, people in this categories who turn out to be defaulters has a considerably higher debt-to-income ratio.

In [24]:
# Dictionary with variables of interest and titles for the plots
varord = {'x_var': ['loan','loan','mortdue', 'property_value'], 
          'y_var' : ['job', 'job', 'job', 'reason'],
          'hue' : ['reason', 'defaulted', 'defaulted', 'defaulted'],
          'title': ['Approved loan by job and reason', 'Approved loan by job and default', 
                   'Mortgage amount due by job', 'Property value by reason of loan']}

# Setting subplots
c=0
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize=(15,15))
for i in range(2):
    c=c+i
    for j in range(2):
        c = c+j
        # Plotting variables of interest
        sns.pointplot(data=data, x= varord['x_var'][c], y=varord['y_var'][c] , hue=varord['hue'][c], 
                      palette ='pastel',ax=ax[i][j])
        
        ax[i][j].set_title(varord['title'][c], fontsize=15)
        ax[i][j].set(xlabel='Dollars') 
        ax[i][j].set(ylabel='')

Observations:¶

  • The loaned amount distributions shows a right-skewed dsitribution with mean and median relatively close, 18,607 dollars and 16,300 dollars, respectively. Few people in dataset have loans approved for more than 40,000 dollars and up to 90,000 dollars.
  • The amount due of existing mortgage shows a right-skewed distribution. Mean and median are 73,760 dollars and 65,019 dollars, respectively, whilst few people due more than, aproximately, 150,000 dollars, even fewer due up to 400,000 dollars.
  • Mortgaged properties value show a right-skewed distribution, with average value of 101,776 dollars and 50% of properties valued under 89,235 dollars. Few properties are valued between 200,000 and 855,000 dollars.
  • In average, debt consolidation has the greatest loan approved among every profession.
  • In average, clients who had smaller loan aproved end up paying their debt. Nevertheless, people with jobs labeled as Sales who had a bigger loan approved turned out to be defaulters.
  • At the same time, in average, people with bigger mortgage amount due payed their debt.
  • On the other hand, people with loans approved for debt consolidation, for both defaulters or not, had in average similar valued properties. In the case of loans approved for home improvement, defaulters had in average, considerably lower valued properties than those who are not defaulters.

In order to get better insight from the number of derogatory reports and number of delinquent credit lines, both variables are transformed into categorical variables, such that, if a person has any report or delinquent credit line, variables are marked with NO, otherwise are marked as Yes. Next secion will calrify this statement.

In this case, dropna() function is used to ignore null values from the dataset and get information only for those people for which information is available.

In [30]:
# Creating two new categorical variables for the number of derogatory reporst and delinquent credit lines

Treating outliers¶

As previously mentioned, variables have clear patterns when grouped by default category. Thus, we will clip outliers for all numerical variables grouped by default and compare the distributions after clipping.

In [51]:
# setting dummy list with number of numerical variables
dv = df.select_dtypes(np.number).columns.tolist()

# Clipping outliers to upper and lower whiskers grouped by default
for i in dv:
    for j in ['Yes', 'No']:
        # setting dummy variable
        nt = df.loc[df['defaulted']==j, i]
        # computing 25th quantile
        q1 = np.quantile(nt, 0.25)
        # computing 75th quantile
        q3 = np.quantile(nt, 0.75)
        # computing interquartile interval
        intq = q3-q1
        # computing upper and lower whisker
        upper = q3 + intq*1.5
        lower = q1 - intq*1.5
        # setting outliers to upper and lower whiskers
        df.loc[df['defaulted']== j, i] = np.clip(nt, lower, upper)

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model evaluation criterion

Next, it is stated the possible predictions for this case and the most important situations in order to minimize the risk of default.

Possible wrong predictions:

  1. The model predicts that a client will default on its loan, but the client actually paid the loan.
  2. The model predicts that a client will pay its loan, but the client defaulted on its loan.

Which case is more important?

  • In the first scenario, the bank would not approve the loan and might lose money from interest.
  • In the second scenario, the bank would approve the loan and lose that money plus the interest.

Hence, the second scenario is more important since the bank would lose more money in the case of approving the loan. Thus, in order to minimize the probabilities of false-negative cases, recall score should be maximized.

Confusion matrix:

  • True-Positive: Predicting that the client will default on its loan and actually does.
  • True-Negative: Predicting that clients will pay their loan and they actually does.
  • False-Positive: Predicting that the client will default on loan but actually paid its loan.
  • False-Negative: Predicting that the client will pay its loan but the client defaulted on its loan.

Once it is established the criteria for the classification algorithms, we proceed to build the models. First, it is defined some functions to meassure the model performance and to plot confussion matrix.

In [55]:
def model_performance(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance
    model: fitted classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    # Predicting values using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)
    
    # Computing F1-score
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred) 
    # Computing Recall score
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average = 'macro') 
    # Computing Precision score
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average = 'macro')     
    # Computing Accuracy score
    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)    
    
    # Creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame({'Precision':  precision,
                            'Recall':  recall,
                            'Accuracy': acc,
                            'F1-score': f1} ,index = ['Score'])
    return df_perf


def conf_matrix(model):
    '''
    Function to plot confusion matrix of both training and testing data.
    
    model: fitted classifier.
    '''
    # Setting list with training and testing data
    xy_data = [[x_train, y_train], [x_test, y_test]]
    
    # Setting subplot axes for plots
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(15,6), sharey=True)
    for i in range(2): 
        # Predicting values on training and testing data
        y_pred = model.predict(xy_data[i][0])
        
        # Generating confussion matrix 
        cm = confusion_matrix(xy_data[i][1],y_pred)
        
        # Plotting confussion matrix on a heatmap
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True,  fmt = '.2f', 
                    xticklabels = ['Defaulted', 'Paid'], yticklabels = ['Defaulted', 'Paid'],
                    cmap=sns.cubehelix_palette(as_cmap=True), cbar=True, ax=ax[i])
        
    # Settiing titles
    fig.suptitle('Confusion matrix', fontsize=20)
    ax[0].set_title('Training data', fontsize=15)
    ax[1].set_title('Testing data', fontsize=15)
    
    
# Getting a list with column names from the dependent variable
features = x.columns.tolist()
def tree_plot(model):    
    '''
    Function to plot the specified model decision tree with depth 3
    model: Fitted classifier
    '''
     # Plotting decision tree with depth = 3
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
    tree.plot_tree(model, feature_names = features, max_depth=3,
                   filled = True, fontsize = 10, 
                   node_ids = False, class_names = ['Defaulted', 'Paid'], label='root')
    
    
def importance(model):
    '''
    Function to plot the feature importance from the specified model
    model: Fitted classifier.
    '''
    # Getting importances 
    importances = model.feature_importances_

    # Creating a dataframe with sorted feature importances
    imp_df = pd.DataFrame(importances, index=features, columns=['Importance']).sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)

    # Plotting importances
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
    sns.barplot(x=imp_df.Importance, y=imp_df.index, palette='pastel')
    plt.title('Feature importance', fontsize=20)
    plt.xlabel('Importance')

Decision tree hyperparameter tuning¶

In order to avoid the model from overfitting it is done below the corresponding fine tuning of hyperparameter. We will make use of GridSearchCV method from Scikit learn to prune the tree, moreover the chosen parameter are the maximum depth, split criterions, minimum samples in leaf node and the maximum features when looking for the best split.

In [64]:
# Adjusting class weights on the classifier
d_tree_tuned = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, class_weight= {0: 0.2, 1: 0.8})

# Grid of hyperparameters to chose
parameters = {'max_depth': np.arange(10,14), 
              'criterion': ['entropy','gini'], 
              'min_samples_leaf': np.arange(5,15),
              'max_features': ['auto', 'sqrt']
             }

# Scoring to compare the parameter combinations. Recall-score for class 1 in this case
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label=1)

# Running Grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(d_tree_tuned, parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=7)

grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Select the best estimator i.e. the tree with highest F1-score
d_tree_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_
print(grid_obj.best_params_)
# Fit the training data to the best estimator
d_tree_tuned.fit(x_train, y_train)

        "n_estimators": [340,345],
        'max_leaf_nodes':[15,12], 
        'max_features': ['auto', 'sqrt']
}

# Scoring to compare the parameter combinations. Recall for class 1 in this case
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label=1)

# Running Grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(rf_clf_tuned, parameter_rf, scoring=recall_score, cv=7)

grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Select the best estimator i.e. the random forest settings with highest recall score
rf_clf_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the training data to the best estimator
rf_clf_tuned.fit(x_train, y_train)

Logistic regression¶

As the final predicting model, it is constructed a logistic regression model. First, it is scaled the since the different scales in variables directly affects the performance of logistic regression.

In [84]:
# Separate independent and dependent variables
yl = ddf['defaulted'].copy()
xl = ddf.copy().drop(columns = ['defaulted'])

# Setting Scikit learn method StandardScaler
sc = StandardScaler()

# Scaling data from independent variables
x_scaled = sc.fit_transform(xl)
x_scaled = pd.DataFrame(x_scaled, columns = xl.columns)

# Split scaled data into training and testing (0.7,0.3 ratio)
xl_train, xl_test, yl_train, yl_test = train_test_split(x_scaled,yl, test_size=0.3, shuffle=True, random_state=1, stratify=yl)

Business insights and recommendations¶

  • The bank should be careful with clients that have a greater debt-to-income ratio since it is the most important feature when predicting if the client will default on its loan. This outcome was expected from the exploratory data analysis as it was pointed that the distributions of debt-to-income for clients who defaulted on its loan was siginificantly higher than those who repaid the loan.
  • Moreover, it makes sense that having a high debt to income ratio will negativily impact the possibility of a person to pay all it debts and loans.
  • Another two important features to take in consideration is the number of derogatory reports and delinquent credit lines. As expected, this variables shows a defaulting pattern since nearly 55% of people with at least one derogatory report or a delinquent credit line defaulted on its loan.
  • On the ohter hand, people with oldest credit lines tends to not default on its loan. This behaviour shows that people who can pay their debts tends to mantain their credit lines active.
  • Finally, the specific profession of the client does not seems to be important to predict whether the client will default on its loan.

Conclusions:

  • It was succesfully built models for predicting loan default with the specific requirement of maximize the recall score in order to minimize the odds of getting false-negative cases.
  • Contrasting performance of different models shows that a random forest is the best predictive model with a recall of, aproximately, 0.94.
  • Overall, all models agrees that the most important features for predicting are the debt-to-income ratio, the number of delinquent credit lines and the number of derogatory reports.
